          <!-- screen -->
          <div class="px-2 m-2 text-3xl font-bold underline" style="width: 96%;">Device Screen</div>
          <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row border-solid border-2 rounded-md shadow-lg p-4 m-4" style="width: 96%;">
            <div class="w-full lg:mt-0 md:w-2/5">
              <img src="images/screen.jpg" alt="screen" class="w-full h-full max-w-md mx-auto">
            </div>
            <div class="p-3 md:w-3/5 text-justify text-lg break-words">
              <p>
                The excessive and compulsive use of digital gadgets like smartphones, tablets, and laptops is called
                device screen
                addiction, also known as screen or technology addiction. This addiction can result in focusing on
                screen-related
                activities that frequently precede other significant facets of life. People could struggle to control
                their screen time,
                feel restless or irritable while not utilizing their devices, and disregard their obligations or
                relationships.
                Addiction to electronic screens can have a severe influence on productivity, sleep, and mental health.
                The first stages
                in managing this addiction and developing a more harmonious relationship with technology are recognizing
                the warning
                signals, setting limits, and forming healthy screen habits.
              </p>
              <p><span class="font-bold underline">Fact:</span> Tech addiction statistics show that people in the 8-28
                age group spend about 44.5 hours a week staring at a screen.
                That's more than most full-time jobs demand of their employees! <a
                  href="https://webtribunal.net/blog/tech-addiction-facts/" target="_blank"
                  class="underline text-[#0000EE]"> (Source)</a></p>
              <p><span class="font-bold underline">Related Links:</span>
